{"add":{"doc":{"id":"d932e9fea78f1b1a43db446d9dcf6c85c6fd3d87406edbea942fa73fffe2cb6c","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Sun_and_Moon_Nuremberg_chronicle.jpg/176px-Sun_and_Moon_Nuremberg_chronicle.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Many methods have been used to simulate mean solar time. The earliest were clepsydras or water clocks, used for almost four millennia from as early as the middle of the 2nd millennium BC until the early 2nd millennium. Before the middle of the 1st millennium BC, the water clocks were only adjusted to agree with the apparent solar day, thus were no better than the shadow cast by a gnomon (a vertical pole), except that they could be used at night."]}}}